13 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
14 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
15 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 11-203 of Title 70, unless there
16 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
17 A. Human growth and development curriculum shall be taught in
18 the public schools of this state. Human growth and development
19 education shall include, but is not limited to:
20 1. Human biology related to pregnancy;
21 2. Human development inside of a womb;
22 3. A high-definition ultrasound video, at least three (3)
23 minutes in duration, showing the development of the fetus in a
24 biological woman; and
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1603 Page 1

1 4. A high-quality, computer-generated rendering or animation
2 showing the process of fetal development, highlighting significant
3 markers in cell growth and organ development until birth.
4 B. School districts shall provide the curriculum described in
5 subsection A of this section to students if the student's parent or
6 legal guardian completes an opt-in permission form. Schools may
7 incorporate the curriculum into an existing course or courses or
8 develop curriculum for a separate course. Schools shall provide
9 parents and legal guardians an opt-in permission form to authorize
10 their child be taught the curriculum described in subsection A of
11 this section two (2) weeks prior to the date the curriculum is to be
12 taught. The opt-in permission shall be on a form prescribed by the
13 State Board of Education and retained by the school district.
14 C. In order to graduate from a public high school accredited by
15 the State Board of Education with a standard diploma, students in
16 grades nine through twelve shall receive human growth and
17 development instruction as described in subsection A of this section
18 unless the student's parent or legal guardian did not complete an
19 opt-in permission form as provided for in subsection B of this
20 section or the student has an Individualized Education Program (IEP)
21 for a significant cognitive disability. Such instruction shall be
22 integrated into health or science education and shall be
23 incorporated into the state academic content standards adopted by
